  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, 'Adaptive Fusion of Distance Metrics via Linguistic-Prior-Conditioned Meta-Loss Optimization,' designed to significantly enhance cross-lingual alignment performance by dynamically combining multiple distance metrics into a unified, adaptive loss function. Traditional alignment methods employ a single fixed metric (e.g., cosine similarity or OT cost), which fails to account for the heterogeneous nature of linguistic divergence across language pairs. Our approach introduces a meta-loss network that learns to optimally weight and combine multiple distance metrics—such as Optimal Transport cost, cosine similarity, Mahalanobis distance, and distributional divergence (e.g., Sinkhorn distance)—based on quantifiable linguistic priors derived from typological databases (e.g., WALS) and learned contextual embeddings. These priors include features like syntactic alignment (SOV vs. SVO), lexical overlap, phonemic inventory distance, and morphological complexity. The meta-loss network is trained using a bilevel optimization scheme: in the inner loop, base alignment models minimize a weighted combination of the multiple metrics; in the outer loop, the meta-loss parameters are updated to maximize alignment accuracy on a validation set of bitexts across diverse language families. Crucially, the fusion weights are not static but generated conditionally per language pair, enabling zero-shot generalization to unseen pairs through interpolation of known linguistic features. We further incorporate uncertainty estimation over metric reliability (e.g., high ambiguity in low-overlap pairs increases reliance on OT over cosine similarity) to make the fusion process robust. This framework enables more precise alignment in both high- and low-resource scenarios, particularly improving performance on distant language pairs where traditional metrics fail. By integrating meta-learning with interpretable linguistic knowledge, our method bridges symbolic typology and neural representation learning, offering both performance gains and model interpretability. Potential impact includes improved multilingual NLP systems, better transfer learning in low-resource languages, and a new paradigm for modular, adaptive loss design in representation alignment tasks.",
